            'In IFS, your exiled Inner Child parts don\'t just carry painful memories — they carry relational expectations. Your Lonely Child expects to be left. Your Unworthy Child expects to be rejected once truly seen. Your Lost Child expects to be ignored. Your Terrified Child expects to be betrayed. Your Powerless Child expects to be dominated. These expectations become self-fulfilling prophecies: they shape what you tolerate, who you choose, and how you show up.',
            'Your protector parts play a crucial role in relationships too. Manager protectors try to prevent wounded parts from being triggered: the Perfectionist makes you perform worthiness, the People-Pleaser eliminates conflict, the Controller manages every variable. Firefighter protectors react when the wound gets touched anyway: the Rager attacks, the Avoider withdraws, the Numbing part reaches for substances or distraction.',
            'Healing your relationship patterns doesn\'t mean becoming a different person — it means having your Self, rather than your wounded parts, lead your relational choices. When your Self leads, you can choose partners who are actually good for you (not just familiar), set boundaries without guilt, express needs without shame, handle conflict without fleeing, and tolerate the vulnerability that intimacy requires.',
